Here is an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP:

**index.php**
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        #search-form {
            width: 50%;
            margin: 20px auto;
        }

        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
        }

        button[type="submit"] {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="search-form">
        <h2>Search Bar</h2>
        <form action="<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="get">
            <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Enter your search query...">
            <button type="submit">Search</button>
        </form>
    </div>

    <?php
    if (isset($_GET['search'])) {
        $searchQuery = $_GET['search'];
        $results = searchDatabase($searchQuery);

        if ($results) { ?>
            <h2>Results:</h2>
            <ul>
                <?php foreach ($results as $result) { ?>
                    <li><a href="<?php echo $result['url']; ?>"><?php echo $result['title']; ?></a></li>
                <?php } ?>
            </ul>
        <?php } else { ?>
            <p>No results found.</p>
        <?php }
    }
    ?>

    <?php
    function searchDatabase($searchQuery) {
        // Connect to database
        $db = mysqli_connect('localhost', 'username', 'password', 'database');

        // Prepare query
        $query = "SELECT * FROM table WHERE column LIKE '%$searchQuery%'";

        // Execute query and retrieve results
        $result = mysqli_query($db, $query);
        return $result;
    }
    ?>
</body>
</html>
```
**Explanation**

This code creates a simple search bar with an input field and a submit button. When the form is submitted, it uses the `searchDatabase` function to query a database using the search query as a parameter.

The `searchDatabase` function connects to the database, prepares a query using the `$searchQuery` variable, executes the query, and returns the results.

**Note**

* This code assumes you have a MySQL database set up with a table named "table" containing a column named "column".
* You should replace the placeholders (`localhost`, `username`, `password`, `database`) with your actual database credentials.
* The `$searchQuery` variable is used to build the SQL query, which may be vulnerable to SQL injection attacks. Consider using prepared statements or parameterized queries instead.

**Example Use Case**

1. Replace the placeholder values in the code with your actual database credentials.
2. Create a table named "table" containing a column named "column" in your MySQL database.
3. Run the code and enter a search query in the input field.
4. Click the "Search" button to execute the query and display the results.

Remember to replace the placeholders with your actual database credentials and adjust the code according to your specific requirements.

